DISTRIBUTION

How a firewall-bridge version reaches consumers — from a local
version bump to a public download from R2.


Pipeline overview
-----------------

  1. Bump        Local script updates all three version sources and
                 creates a single commit on dev/firewall-bridge.
  2. Push        Push the bump commit. Two CI workflows fire
                 automatically: test and build. They produce artifacts
                 but do not publish.
  3. Verify      Operator inspects the test + build artifacts on the
                 GitHub Actions run page. No release happens until the
                 operator is satisfied.
  4. Publish     Operator runs publish.sh, which dispatches the publish
                 workflow with no arguments.
  5. R2 upload   Publish workflow re-runs test + build, validates that
                 the Python and Cargo version sources agree, then
                 uploads to R2 under both versioned and latest paths.
  6. Consumption Downstream consumers fetch a per-arch zip from
                 vendor.phantom.tc over HTTPS.


Stage 1 — Bump
--------------

  .github/scripts/bump.sh [major|minor|patch]

  Defaults to patch. Updates ALL three version locations atomically:

      firewall_bridge/__init__.py  →  __version__
      Cargo.toml                   →  [package] version
      Cargo.lock                   →  [[package]] firewall-bridge-linux version

  Refuses to run if the three are already out of sync. Verifies the
  post-write values, then creates a single commit:

      Bump v<NEW_VERSION>

  Only the three version files are staged.


Stage 2 — Push
--------------

  git push origin dev/firewall-bridge

  Two workflows fire on the bump commit (and on every push to this
  branch that touches non-.github paths):

      test-firewall-bridge.yml     Three parallel jobs:
                                     test-rust    cargo test inside the
                                                  Docker dev container
                                                  (.so + headers needed
                                                  to link).
                                     test-python  pytest unit suite via
                                                  Docker SDK runner —
                                                  195 tests across db,
                                                  bridge, types,
                                                  presets, schema,
                                                  ffi-discovery.
                                     e2e          compose-bridge driven
                                                  multihop scenarios for
                                                  IPv4 and IPv6 (2 e2e
                                                  tests).

      build-firewall-bridge.yml    Two native builds (no cross-compile):
                                     build-linux-amd64   ubuntu-latest
                                     build-linux-arm64   ubuntu-24.04-arm
                                   Artifacts:
                                     firewall-bridge-linux-amd64 (90d)
                                     firewall-bridge-linux-arm64 (90d)
                                   Each contains .so + .h + .sha256 +
                                   firewall_bridge/*.py + schemas/.

  Neither workflow uploads to R2. They exist to give the operator a
  pass/fail signal and downloadable artifacts for inspection.


Stage 3 — Verify
----------------

  The operator opens the GitHub Actions run page and confirms all
  three test jobs (rust, python, e2e) and both build jobs are green.
  If anything is wrong, follow-up commits land on top of the bump
  commit. The bump itself is rarely amended — the version stays the
  same and the fixes ride on top.


Stage 4 — Publish trigger
-------------------------

  .github/scripts/publish.sh

  No arguments. Reads the version from
  firewall_bridge/__init__.py and dispatches
  publish-firewall-bridge.yml on the dev/firewall-bridge ref via the
  GitHub CLI (gh workflow run).


Stage 5 — Publish workflow
--------------------------

  publish-firewall-bridge.yml runs four jobs in sequence:

      version    Extracts the version from __init__.py.
                 Validates that Cargo.toml [package] version matches.
                 Aborts the entire run on mismatch.

      test       Re-runs the full test suite via workflow_call —
                 test-rust + test-python + e2e. Treated as a release
                 gate; failure stops the publish.

      build      Re-runs the native amd64 and arm64 builds via
                 workflow_call.

      publish    Self-hosted runner with rclone configured against the
                 R2 remote. Packages each architecture into a zip,
                 verifies sha256 checksums, uploads to R2 under both
                 v<VERSION>/ and latest/ paths.


Stage 6 — R2 storage
--------------------

  Bucket : phantom-vendor
  Domain : vendor.phantom.tc

  Each publish writes to two locations simultaneously:

      firewall-bridge/v<VERSION>/      pinned, immutable
      firewall-bridge/latest/          moves on every publish

  Both contain the same three files:

      linux-amd64.zip     Python package + .so + .h for linux/amd64
      linux-arm64.zip     Python package + .so + .h for linux/arm64
      VERSION             plain-text version string at the path level

  Each zip contains a single top-level firewall_bridge/ directory:

      firewall_bridge/
        __init__.py
        _ffi.py
        bridge.py
        db.py
        models.py
        presets.py
        schema.py
        types.py
        schemas/
          schema.sql
        libfirewall_bridge_linux.so
        libfirewall_bridge_linux.so.sha256
        firewall_bridge_linux.h
        VERSION

  The VERSION file is duplicated (path-level + inside the zip) so
  consumers can tell which version they have without unzipping.


Stage 7 — Consumption
---------------------

  Consumers download over HTTPS. Two strategies:

      Pinned to a known version (recommended):
        https://vendor.phantom.tc/firewall-bridge/v<VERSION>/linux-amd64.zip

      Tracking the moving latest pointer:
        https://vendor.phantom.tc/firewall-bridge/latest/linux-amd64.zip

  After extraction, the runtime version can be confirmed two ways:

      cat firewall_bridge/VERSION
      python -c "from firewall_bridge import __version__; print(__version__)"

  Both should agree with the URL the artifact came from. If they
  disagree, the deployed copy was tampered with or the build pipeline
  has a bug — either way, do not use it.


End-to-end example
------------------

  $ .github/scripts/bump.sh patch
  2.1.4 → 2.1.5
  [dev/firewall-bridge abcdef0] Bump v2.1.5

  $ git push origin dev/firewall-bridge
  ...
  # → test (rust + python + e2e) and build (amd64 + arm64) workflows
  #   fire on GitHub Actions.

  # Operator opens the run page, confirms green checks across all
  # five jobs.

  $ .github/scripts/publish.sh
  Version : v2.1.5
  Workflow: publish-firewall-bridge.yml
  Ref     : dev/firewall-bridge
  Triggered. Watch: gh run list --repo ARAS-Workspace/phantom-wg --workflow publish-firewall-bridge.yml

  # → publish workflow runs version → test → build → publish.
  #   R2 receives the new artifacts.

  # Consumers can now fetch:
  #   https://vendor.phantom.tc/firewall-bridge/v2.1.5/linux-amd64.zip
  #   https://vendor.phantom.tc/firewall-bridge/latest/linux-amd64.zip


Rollback
--------

  No artifacts are deleted from R2. If a bad version goes out:

  1. Bump again (patch) and publish a new fixed version. The latest/
     path moves forward to the new build immediately.

  2. Pinned consumers stay on the bad version until they update
     their pin. Communicate the issue out-of-band.

  3. Optionally rewrite latest/ manually to point at the previous
     known-good v<VERSION>/ contents using rclone — but this leaves
     the bad bits at v<VERSION>/, so prefer step 1.


Notes
-----

  * Changes under .github/ do not trigger test/build on push
    (paths-ignore on the workflows).

  * The test workflow runs the same Docker topology used in local
    development — no environment drift between local and CI.

  * arm64 builds on a native ubuntu-24.04-arm runner (no cross-
    compile), so the produced .so is exactly what an arm64 host
    would see.

  * Publish runs on a self-hosted runner because the R2 credentials
    live there, not in GitHub Secrets.

  * The standalone VERSION file at the R2 path level lets consumers
    do a HEAD-style check ("what version is at latest/ right now?")
    without downloading a multi-megabyte zip.
